 and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":16,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Matida Etchingham was born about 1274, in Etchingham, Sussex, England. She had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Richard de Etchingham. She died on 16 February 1307, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1274–16 February 1307":"umbes 1274–16. veebruar 1307","1272–1296":"1272–1296","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1302–Female":"1302–Surnud","1274–1307":"1274–1307","about 1290":"umbes 1290","16 February 1307":"16. veebruar 1307","1274":"1274","1296":"1296","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1298":"1298","about 1302":"umbes 1302","Aft 1296":"pärast 1296","about 1300":"umbes 1300","about 1298":"umbes 1298","1307":"1307","about 1274":"umbes 1274","Of,Echingham,Sussex,England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Etchingham, Sussex, England":"Etchingham, Sussex,